                {
                    "id" : "prerequisites",
                    "text" : [ "<p><span id=\"htZoomImageMsg\"></span></p>",
                        { "text" : "### Prerequisites\n\nThe development of writing systems occurred after the beginning of counting by our species. Therefore, we recommend that readers first study the text on creating numerical patterns and their prerequisites",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "e141ef0d-690f-4109-aad2-0691181b04ca",
                                                "text": "History Tracers Team, <i>Making Patterns</i>",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2024", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }} ],
                                  "isTable" : false,
                                  "format" : "markdown",
                                  "PostMention": "."
                               }]
                },
                {
                    "id" : "introduction",
                    "text" : [ { "text" : "### Introduction\n\nAround thirty thousand years ago, our species began to move beyond counting with just our bodies, initially adopting bar markings to register quantities. Based on the way counting is organized on bones, as shown in Figure 1, it is understood that the creation of these patterns was inspired by the human body",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "a4f22e25-5839-407f-a1aa-634521d52b42",
                                                "text": "González Redondo, Francisco A., et al.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2010", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "ceffba8a-43be-4de3-a5c8-27cdf81311b1",
                                                "text": "Puente, Francisco Barriga",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2020", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }} ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": "."
                               },
                                "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgHueso\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgHueso', '0%')\" src=\"images/Figura-9-Hueso-de-Lebombo.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 1: Representation of baboon bone adorned with markings. This image, credited to Enrique Silván Pobes, is featured in the scholarly work of Francisco A. Gonzáles Redondo et al.<br />The original is available in ResearchNet (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('adaed4fb-9c50-4ef9-ab79-c65f3c0629b8'); return false;\">González Redondo, Francisco A., et al., <span class=\"htdate\"></span></a>), and its inclusion here is made possible by the authorization of Doctor Francisco A. Gonzales Redondo.</p>"
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id" : "pattern",
                    "text" : [ { "text" : "### Writing system\n\nDuring the time, differentes writing systems arised independently around the world, motivated by necessity of business, believes and preservation of knowledge. These systems had na essential role in our ideas and talking through texts",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "cf5ef4bb-268a-4885-98ee-6a9af3c221d3",
                                                "text": "Abdul Karim Khan, 01:10:25",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2013", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "73c1fc70-769e-47cb-a7b4-597a73d21a93",
                                                "text": "Dr. Irving Finkel, 00:05:00",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2019", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "cd61bc64-1358-4bfd-b343-3629facaa3b4",
                                                "text": "González Redondo, Francisco A., 00:10:39",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2024", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": "."
                               },
                               { "text" : "In this section, we opt to present the writing systems using the same order used in Cradle of Civilization in section *General History* to simplify content comparison. This will simplify content comparison",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "867968ea-62d6-4a8a-b3a0-8b82c76d86bf",
                                                "text": "History Tracers Team",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2024", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }} ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": "."
                               },
                                "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgMWPWEEC\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgMWPWEEC', '0%')\" src=\"images/mapswire/mapswire-world-political-white-equal_earth_cradle.png\" class=\"imgcenterlarge\"/>Figure 2: Cradle of Civilization. © Mapswire (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('dd4f3c8a-6624-4df5-93ac-37e0a4be9fdc'); return false;\"><i>Mapswire</i></a>). Compartilhado sob a licença <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0)</p>",
                               { "text" : "#### Mesopotamia\n\nMesopotamian languages belong to the Semitic language family, known for their shared morphology. However, modern linguistic research suggests that these languages are not the original source but instead evolved from an earlier group known as Proto-Afro-Asiatic languages. A notable example of ancient text written in this language family is the **Sumerian King List**, housed in the Ashmolean Museum in Oxford",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "ce66881d-74fd-4dac-837c-07c77d1bc2a6",
                                                "text": "Wolff, H. Ekkehard",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2024", "month" : "6", "day" : "26" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "b4095535-0080-4782-8cbd-1914b34ec8a6",
                                                "text": "Testen, D.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2024", "month" : "9", "day" : "23" }},
                                              { "type": 0,
                                                "uuid": "72b8a10d-1a15-4a10-aff6-1210b7bd94fc",
                                                "text": "Sumerian King List. <i>Ashmolean Museum Oxford</i>",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2024", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "d44ac38d-76e3-472d-8608-2fc47f40759a",
                                                "text": "Cartwright, M.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2024", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": ":"
                               },
                              "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgKingList\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgKingList', '0%')\" src=\"images/Ashmolean/KingList.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 3: Image © Ashmolean Museum, University of Oxford (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('4d0b579d-57af-45e1-87b0-d402dd778968'); return false;\">Ashmolean Image Library</a>).</p>",
                               { "text" : "#### Andes\n\nFor a period of time, there was resistance to recognizing the Incas as a civilization comparable to others previously known, due to the apparent absence of writing systems in the Andes region. However, recent studies suggest that the knots (<i>quipus</i>) may represent more than just a numerical system, potentially containing information analogous to writing. If confirmed as a writing system, the quipus would signify a millennia-old tradition of record-keeping and communication",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "c2ff41fc-7833-4dc2-8882-eaed12a065b7",
                                                "text": "Mann, Charles C., pp. 1008",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2005", "month" : "6", "day" : "26" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "2ebd3420-941b-4f17-b5bc-17bb39ef37a0",
                                                "text": "Hyland, S.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2017", "month" : "11", "day" : "7" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "b74bf294-c758-4a48-88c9-399ca4f021f6",
                                                "text": "Cartwright, M.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2014", "month" : "5", "day" : "8" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "b915dbab-73e6-46e6-ac52-415882cba1fd",
                                                "text": "Laurencich Minelli, L.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2016", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "75ca7e93-6ffd-4303-b21d-b669592dcde3",
                                                "text": "Urton, G.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2019", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "6b010ce5-ea7c-4a21-a416-99404c66d2e8",
                                                "text": "Moras, Roberto",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2024", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "f1bfa7e1-c7c2-408e-9b36-d955c119d323",
                                                "text": "Moras, Roberto",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2024", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": "."
                               },
                               "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgQuipuPanel\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgQuipuPanel', '0%')\" src=\"images/QuipuPanel.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 4: Panel at the archaeological site of Caral, ©ZonaArqueólogicaCaral, (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('720f6dfd-4b86-4e07-a887-1010e1041a4d'); return false;\">Ruta Caral, <span class=\"htdate\"></span></a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('03c3743c-d268-4730-ba8e-d36b5c49e781'); return false;\">Youtube - Caral Perú Oficial, <span class=\"htdate\"></span></a>). Photo taken on <span class=\"htdate\"></span> during a visit to the site.</p>",
                               { "text" : "#### Mesoamerica\n\nAmong Mesoamerican civilizations, the hieroglyphic writing system played a fundamental role in recording the histories of cultures such as the Maya, Zapotec, and Aztec",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "352702e1-3043-4a94-8f4b-12e98442d91d",
                                                "text": "Mora-Marín, D. F.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2009", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "06add118-bff5-45bb-9faa-ad6af95a7725",
                                                "text": "Oudijk, Michel R.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2004", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "f0f4c9bd-29cc-4e64-a7da-22de34c200b7",
                                                "text": "Kettunen, Harri et al.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2010", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": "."
                               },
                               "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgCopanWholeTextSA\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgCopanWholeTextSA', '0%')\" src=\"images/CopanWholeTextStelaAltar.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 5: Altar, stela, and the largest hieroglyphic text found at the archaeological site of Copán (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('1e007481-9bd3-4a09-ad4d-6e812fe79641'); return false;\">Instituto Hondureño de Antropologia e Historia, <span class=\"htdate\"></span></a>). Photo taken on <span class=\"htdate\"></span> during a visit to the site.</p>",
                               { "text" : "#### Egypt\n\nMesoamerica was not the only cradle of civilization to use hieroglyphs. The Egyptians were the first to adopt this system, which could also be the first writing system developed in history; however, this remains a topic of debate. Although both civilizations used hieroglyphs, there is no connection between their systems. Figure 6 illustrates a fragment of text listing some of the kings who preceded Ramses II",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 0,
                                                "uuid": "22c45ac9-4986-4add-afba-1d8fd90916a9",
                                                "text": "<i>The British Museum</i>"},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "e94c9f0d-d9e6-4ff3-8634-e9aea3a82509",
                                                "text": "Cy, 06:40",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2023", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "61bd4123-d735-45f0-9acc-607d50201477",
                                                "text": "Amin, O. S. M.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2016", "month" : "7", "day" : "21" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "87136322-0b7b-4f23-b76b-101fce2940f0",
                                                "text": "Mattessich, Richard",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2002", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": "."
                               },
                               "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgEgypt\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgEgypt', '0%')\" src=\"images/BritshMuseum/mid_00178382_001.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 6: Abydos King List. © Trustees of the British Museum (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('22c45ac9-4986-4add-afba-1d8fd90916a9'); return false;\"><i>The British Museum</i></a>).</p>",
                               { "text" : "#### Indus Valley Civilization\n\nThe commonalities among the cradles of civilization are not limited to hieroglyphs. Similar to the Andean civilizations, where the existence of a writing system is presumed to have helped administer a vast empire, the Indus Valley Civilization also developed a writing system that remains undeciphered",
                                 "source" : [ 
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "b2f2b9dc-e8d0-4589-8b36-529ea7f24e09",
                                                "text": "Abdul Karim Khan, 18:29",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2013", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "89b0df4e-5e0f-4343-9912-07bc95ea3d7c",
                                                "text": "Violatti, C.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2015", "month" : "7", "day" : "5" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": "."
                               },
                               "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgHarappaW\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgHarappaW', '0%')\" src=\"images/Ashmolean/28932.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 7: Harappa Seal. © Ashmolean Museum, University of Oxford (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('1696d647-d450-44e3-9067-18aac69bce3d'); return false;\">Ashmolean Museum Oxford</a>). Compartilhado sob a licença <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0).</p>",
                               { "text" : "#### Chinese Civilization\n\nThe Chinese pictogram system has its earliest records, which have reached us through inscriptions on bones. It is possible that other organic materials were also used, but these have not survived over time. This writing system developed independently, without any interaction with the Sumerian writing system, as was once suggested by some researchers ",
                                 "source" : [ 
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "cf5ef4bb-268a-4885-98ee-6a9af3c221d3",
                                                "text": "Abdul Karim Khan, 53:18",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2013", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "b2f2b9dc-e8d0-4589-8b36-529ea7f24e09",
                                                "text": "Abdul Karim Khan, 01:10:20",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2013", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }
                                              }
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": "."
                               },
                               "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgChinese\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgChinese', '0%')\" src=\"images/BritshMuseum/mid_RRC5932_14.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 8: Arrowhead made from bone, featuring inscriptions. © Trustees of the British Museum (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('874a8d48-a892-4ad3-8bc4-b34190bd4eba'); return false;\"><i>The British Museum</i></a> ).</p>"
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id" : "conclusion",
                    "text" : [ { "text" : "### Conclusion\n\nIn this introductory text, we explored the first writing systems that emerged across various civilizations around the world.\n\nWe observed that while some writing systems may be classified similarly, they do not share the same origin. There is no archaeological evidence directly connecting the groups responsible for their creation, reinforcing the idea that \"to look alike\" does not necessarily mean \"to be the same.\"\n\nBefore continuing with our study of text interpretation, we propose a reflection on a topic touched upon here, which will be explored further in the next steps",
                                 "source" : null,
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": ":"
                               },
                                "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: Encountering the Unknown</b><br /><br />When examining the writing systems developed in Africa, Europe, and Asia—geographically interconnected continents—we observe that their characteristics are strikingly different from the Andean quipus. On the other hand, in Mesoamerica, we encounter a hieroglyphic writing system that developed independently from the three previously mentioned continents.<br /><br />Could the uniqueness of the Andean system, compared to others, explain why we have succeeded in understanding Mesoamerican hieroglyphs but still face challenges in confirming or fully deciphering the Andean writing system?</div></div></center></p>"
                    ]
                },
